'''Al-Harith ibn Abi’l-ʿAlaʾ Saʿid ibn Hamdan al-Taghlibi''' (932–968), better known by his ''[[nom de plume]]'' of '''Abu Firas al-Hamdani''' ({{lang-ar|أبو فراس الحمداني}}), was an [[Arab]] prince and poet. He was a cousin of [[Sayf al-Dawla]] and a member of the noble family of the [[Hamdanid dynasty|Hamdanids]], who were rulers in northern [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] and [[Upper Mesopotamia]] during the 10th century. He served Sayf al-Dawla as governor of [[Manbij]] as well as court poet, and was active in his cousin's wars against the [[Byzantine Empire]]. He was captured by the Byzantines in 962 and spent four years in their capital, [[Constantinople]], where he composed his most famous work, the collection of poems titled ''al-Rūmiyyāt'' (الروميات). He was killed in 968, when he raised a revolt against Sayf al-Dawla's successor [[Sa'd al-Dawla|Abu'l-Ma'ali]]. He is considered among the greatest figures of classical [[Arabic poetry]].

==Life==
[[File:Hamdanid family tree.svg|thumb|right|250px|Family tree of the Hamdanids]]
He was born in 932 or in 933, probably in [[Iraq]] and specifically in [[Baghdad]], as his father [[Sa'id ibn Hamdan|Abi'l-Ala Sa'id]]—a son of the [[Hamdanid]] family's founder, [[Hamdan ibn Hamdun]]—occupied a distinguished position in the court of the [[Abbasid]] caliph [[al-Muqtadir]] (reigned 908–932). Abu Firas' mother was a [[Byzantine Greeks|Byzantine Greek]] slave concubine (an ''[[Islamic_views_on_slavery#Concubinage|umm walad]]'', freed after giving birth to her master's child). His maternal descent later was a source of scorn and taunts from his Hamdanid relatives, a fact reflected in his poems.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|pp=315–316}} 

His father was killed in 935, during a dispute over possession of [[Mosul]] with his nephew, [[Nasir al-Dawla]], and Abu Firas' mother fled to the protection of Nasir al-Dawla's brother, [[Sayf al-Dawla]], and when the latter occupied [[Aleppo]] and northern [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] in 944/5, Abu Firas was welcomed at his cousin's court.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=316}} There he was raised under the supervision of Sayf al-Dawla, who also married his sister. Aside from being a renowned warrior, Sayf al-Dawla was famous for his patronage of scholars and poets, and the young Abu Firas grew up in a culturally vibrant atmosphere, which saw assembled at Aleppo some of the finest minds of the Muslim world: the preacher [[Ibn Nubatah]], the philosopher and musician [[al-Farabi]], and the great poet [[al-Mutanabbi]], while the grammarian [[Ibn Khalawayh]] was his tutor.{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|pp=315, 317}}

[[File:Arab-Byzantine frontier zone.svg|thumb|right|250px|Map of the Arab–Byzantine frontier zone, where Abu Firas was active]]
Abu Firas soon distinguished himself both for his martial as well as for his literary ability, and in 947/8, Sayf al-Dawla appointed him governor of [[Manbij]], close to the border with the [[Byzantine Empire]], to which the governorship of [[Harran]] was later added. Despite his youth, he distinguished himself both in the conflicts with the [[Nizari]] tribes of the [[Diyar Mudar]] and the [[Syrian desert]], as well as in his cousin's frequent raiding campaigns into Byzantine territory.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=317}} Thus, in 952, he defeated the Byzantines under [[Bardas Phokas the Younger]] or his son [[Constantine Phokas]], when the latter tried to interfere with Sayf al-Dawla's refortification of the towns of [[Ra'ban]] and [[Mar'ash]] in the frontier zone.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū Firās al-Ḥāriṯ b. Saʻīd b. Ḥamdān (#20051)}} His captivity by the Byzantines is variously dated by the Arabic sources.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū Firās al-Ḥāriṯ b. Saʻīd b. Ḥamdān (#20051)}} According to [[Ibn Khallikan]], he was first captured by the Byzantines in 959, but escaped captivity at the fortress of Kharshana by jumping into the [[Euphrates]]; this tale is however dismissed by some modern commentators.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=317}} Most sources place his capture in 962 (in November, according to [[Ibn al-Athir]]). The Byzantine general [[Theodore Parsakoutenos]] led a raid of 1,000 or 1,300 men in the vicinity of Manbij, and when Abu Firas set out with only seventy men to obstruct their plundering, he was captured. According to [[Izz al-Din ibn Shaddad|Ibn Shaddad]], however, who reports the story with slight differences, this event took place in 959/60.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū Firās al-Ḥāriṯ b. Saʻīd b. Ḥamdān (#20051)}}

Parsakoutenos tried to have his high-ranking prisoner exchanged with his own brother and father, who had become prisoners of Sayf al-Dawla at [[Hadath]] in 954.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū Firās al-Ḥāriṯ b. Saʻīd b. Ḥamdān (#20051)}} Nevertheless, and despite sending repeated letters to his cousin pleading for his release, Abu Firas spent several years as a captive at the Byzantine capital [[Constantinople]], until released in the [[Arab–Byzantine prisoner exchanges|prisoner exchange]] at [[Samosata]] in 966. During his captivity, Abu Firas wrote some of his "finest poetry", the collection known as ''al-Rūmiyyāt'' ([[Rûm|Rūm]] was the Arab name for the Byzantines).{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|pp=317–318}} In the meantime, Abu Firas' mother had died, her passing a source of lamentation in Abu Firas' poetry.{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=322}}

After his release, Abu Firas was restored to his position and was named governor of [[Homs]], but the situation was rapidly changing: less than a year after his release, Sayf al-Dawla died, and the Hamdanid emirate of Aleppo began to crumble. Abu Firas quickly quarrelled with Sayf al-Dawla's 15-year-old heir, [[Sa'd al-Dawla|Abu'l-Ma'ali]], the son of Abu Firas' own sister, Sakhinah. Overestimating the support he enjoyed among the Arab tribes, Abu Firas revolted against his nephew, but was defeated and killed on 4 April 968 by Abu'l-Ma'ali's general [[Karghawayh]]. At the news of his death, Sakhinah was reportedly so overcome with grief, that she plucked out one of her own eyes.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=326}}

==Work and legacy==
Abu Firas enjoys a prominent position among the greats of classical [[Arabic poetry]]. His near-contemporary, the eminent scholar and statesman [[Sahib ibn Abbad]], summed up the esteem in which Abu Firas was held already in the 10th century in a phrase that was frequently quoted by later authorities: "Poetry began with a king (i.e. [[Imru al-Qays]]) and ended with a king (i.e. Abu Firas)".{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=327}} The corpus of his works was edited after his death by Ibn Khalawayh, who also attached a commentary, largely written by Abu Firas himself. Nevertheless, in later times several manuscript versions of his works with significant variations between them were extant, which indicates that Ibn Khalawayh's edition was not the only one.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}

Abu Firas' early work comprises poems in the classical ''[[qasida|qaṣīda]]'' form in praise of the Hamdanids and their deeds—the 225-line ''Ḥamdāniyyah'' is perhaps the most notable—and shorter poems in the ''ʿIrāqī'' form on courtly themes of love, wine, hunting and friendship. He also produced several pro-[[Shi'ite]] poems attacking the Abbasids.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|pp=316, 318}} Although his early works and the ''al-Rūmiyyāt'' inevitably show al-Mutanabbi's influence, Abu Firas was the great poet's rival, encouraged by his tutor Ibn Khalawayh, a bitter opponent of al-Mutanabbi.{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=318}} According to [[H.A.R. Gibb]], the ''qasida'' poems "are remarkable for their sincerity, directness, and natural vigour", in contrast to the elaborate style of al-Mutanabbi, while the ''ʿIrāqī'' poems are merely "elegant trifles, formal and unoriginal".{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}} It is the ''al-Rūmiyyāt'', however, and their "combination [...] of pathos, dignity, and pride" (El Tayib) that have secured Abu Firas' place among the greats of Arabic poetry.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|El Tayib|1990|p=327}} In addition, according to H.A.R. Gibb, his personal traits helped spread his reputation: from his noble descent and fair appearance, his bravery and generosity, to his tendency to egotism and over-reaching ambition, "he lived up to the Arab ideal of chivalry which he expressed in his poetry".{{sfn|Gibb|1986|pp=119–120}}

